==English==
===Noun===
'''[[fire]] [[drill]]'''
#An organised practice to prepare occupants of an office, school or other public building for evacuation in the event of a fire.
#{{idiom}} any [[pointless]], [[unproductive]], [[useless]], or [[chaotic]] activity (sometimes '''Chinese fire drill''', but this usage is becoming [[outmoded]] in an age of [[politically correct|political correctness]])
#:''Since they changed the standards again, our previous efforts now just amount to a '''fire drill'''.''
#{{idiom}} any [[chaotic]], [[unexpected]] activity. (With the dropping of '''Chinese''' the phrase has also often lost its pejorative meaning of [[pointless]] and [[unproductive]]. In this way, ''fire drill'' is often used in the same idiomatic way ''putting out fires'' or ''fire fighting'' is used.)
#:''Sorry I didn't get back to you earlier, I've been involved in a '''fire drill''' all afternoon.''